defaultThe James Hutton Institute welcomes the opportunity to provide views to the UK Parliament on the public understanding of climate change and its policy implications. The Institute was formed on 1
defaultst
default April 2011 when SCRI (Scottish Crop Research Institute) and the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute joined forces to create one of the world’s leading scientific organisations focusing on 
defaultpeople, 
defaultland, crops, water and the environment. The Institute has a significant programme of inter
default-
defaultdisciplinary research 
default(including social sciences) 
defaulton climate change as it relates to food, water security, and provision of ecosystem services. Staff at the Institute have coordinated and been partners in research projects looking at all aspects of climate change for funders including policy makers such as 
defaultthe 
defaultScottish Government and the EU. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis response 
defaultis based on research undertaken by the James Hutton Institute, partners and in the broader literature,
default from natural and social scientists working on different aspects of climate change including mitigation, adaptation, and significance, risk and uncertainty. 
