default&#xa0;
defaultClimate change related to energy:
default2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultE
defaultnvironmental NGOs and other third sector actors are the most trusted sources of influence in relation to energy saving (GILDED European Policy Brief 4). This is followed by the media, Authorities (e.g.
default Government energy departments
default) and friends, which are ahead of central government and local government, with EU politic
defaultian
defaults and authorities coming last. 
default2.1.1.
default 
defaultTh
defaultis 
defaultsuggest that government, advisers and scientists should concentrate on building the existing consensus, that current resource use is unsustainable, rather than attempting to convince the public of the scientific view on climate change.
default2.1.2.
default 
defaultThe GILDED project provides evidence that individuals show a preference for a lead to be taken by government (at EU, National and local levels) through allowing public bodies and stakeholder partnerships to demonstrate the benefits of action across different sectors, such as infrastructure, transport and energy planning. 
default2.1.3.
default 
defaultInternational policy (e.g. EU) should enable national governments and industry leaders to implement tangible GHG reduction practices alongside policies focused at other levels 
default(Nijnik and Bizikova, 2008), (
defaulte.g. household, individual) in order to engender a sense of shared responsibility for action. 
default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEvidence suggests that policymakers and local authorities have a role to play in drawing attention to business models 
defaultthat
default demonstrate continued profits as a result of responding to climate change policies, such as reducing GHG emissions. 
default2.2.1.
default 
defaultPolicy incentives that encourage business leadership are required to build public acceptance of the need to adopt more climate friendly lifestyles. In environments where public funding might be scarce such policies may be the main drivers for achieving overall policy goals relating to addressing climate change. 
default2.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultI
defaultnformation and advice on climate change policy needs to be clear, consistent and linked to feedback on the impact that collective action is making. Such information needs to relate primarily to tangible goals and behaviours, such as reducing energy or increasing recycling, which are easier for people to relate to than more abstract concepts relating to climate change in general.
default&#xa0;
default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn developing communication approaches to improve public understanding of climate change leading to positive behavioural responses, it is necessary to understand the range and variability of individuals
default and communities
default, the motivations that influence them and how they react to information.
default3.1.1.
default 
defaultCommunication of uncertainty should address the range of possible variability and how this might affect people.
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst
default policy and market forces are the primary drivers of behaviour change, social norms and relationships with peers and friends within communities do influence decision-makin
defaultg and uptake of new behaviours.
default3.2.1.
default 
defaultEnvironmental values can be developed from an early age via family, peers, formal and informal education, media including television, books, 
defaultnewspapers, 
defaultma
defaultgazines and 
defaultnew social media
default:
default 
defaultthe internet
default, social networking, blogs etc
default.
default3.2.2.
default 
defaultWhile knowledge on its own is not usually sufficient to drive behaviour change, educational policy that promotes an understanding of the science underlying environment issues means that individuals are better equipped to make future decisions to adopt pro-environmental behaviours.
default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultStakeholders who mediate between individuals and their communities and regional authorities are recognised as key to building partnerships and networks necessary for coo
defaultrdinated policy implementation.
default3.3.1.
default 
defaultSuch third sector actors (NGOs, community development groups etc.), can be powerful stakeholders because they mediate between households and those implementing policy at different levels and therefore have considerable leverage on the degree to which policies can influence behaviour. 
default3.3.2.
default 
defaultP
defaultublic and private bodies need to continue efforts to engage in network building, showcasing examples of good practice, and these should improve the transmission of information and skills
default (Bizikova et al., 2012)
default. This includes identification of local stakeholders who may become drivers of energy saving and awareness raising, and whose economic interests and moral commitments are associated with energy saving and use of renewable sources.
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSurveys of climate change issues may be problematic in that there is heterogeneity in responses due to 
defaultmotivation and ability to process information in decision strategies (Fischer and Glenk 2011).
default3.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClimate scepticism may be particularly common amongst older people from lower socio-economic backgrounds who are conservative and hold traditional values (Tradition, Conformity, Security). In contrast, climate scepticism was less common among younger people from higher socio-economic backgrounds who hold self-transcendence (Universalism, Benevolence) and environmental values. 
defaultW
defaulthilst those non-sceptical of climate change showed attitudinal certainty, those scept
defaultical of climate change did not, suggesting
default that people who are sceptical might be easily convinced of its true nature. This in turn suggests that public understanding of climate change might be improved by concentrating on changing the attitudes of 
defaultsceptics
default 
default(Poortinga et al 2011)
default.
default3.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe media
default (traditional and new social)
default, along with 
defaultscientists and 
defaultother stakeholders
default (including teachers and education professionals)
default, 
defaultcan
default play a positive role in assisting with information exchange between different levels, building networks of activists and tra
defaultnsferring skills and knowledge.
default3.6.1.
default 
defaultBut this can be reversed 
defaultor distorted 
defaultif powerful sceptics influence the
defaultse
default media
default types
